result_summary.diagnosis_reasoning: This diagnosis is selected based on ABC prioritization (Breathing compromise). The assessment data clearly demonstrates current respiratory dysfunction: SpO2 92% (below normal 95-100%), respiratory rate 28/min (elevated for age 7, normal 18-25), bilateral crackles on auscultation, increased work of breathing with mild retractions and nasal flaring, and chest X-ray showing bilateral infiltrates consistent with pneumonia. These findings indicate actual impairment in oxygenation at the alveolar-capillary membrane level. While 'ineffective airway clearance' addresses secretion management, 'impaired gas exchange' takes priority because it reflects the underlying pathophysiology of pneumonia affecting oxygen-carbon dioxide exchange at the cellular level, which is more immediately life-threatening. The elevated WBC (15,200) and infiltrates confirm an infectious process compromising gas exchange. Hyperthermia, though present (39.2Â°C), is a lower physiological priority than breathing/oxygenation per ABC framework. This is an actual problem with clear evidence of compromise, not merely a risk, making it the highest priority diagnosis.
